o4-mini Answer:
A convenient way to see the region is to note that it is

 R = {(x,y,z) | 1 ≤ x²+y² ≤ 4−z²} 

or equivalently

 R = {(x,y,z) | x²+y²+z² ≤ 4, x²+y² ≥ 1}.

We will write three different triple integrals all of which equal

 Vol(R) = ∬∬_R 1 dV.

---

1)  Rectangular coordinates

One way is to keep x the outermost variable, break at x=±1, and for each x enforce 1≤x²+y²≤4−z².  For example

Vol(R)
= ∫_{x=−2}^{−1}
    ∫_{y=−√(4−x²)}^{√(4−x²)}
      ∫_{z=−√(4−x²−y²)}^{√(4−x²−y²)} 1 dz dy dx
  + ∫_{x=−1}^{1}
    ( ∫_{y=−√(4−x²)}^{−√(1−x²)}
      + ∫_{y=√(1−x²)}^{√(4−x²)} )
      ∫_{z=−√(4−x²−y²)}^{√(4−x²−y²)} 1 dz dy
    dx
  + ∫_{x=1}^{2}
    ∫_{y=−√(4−x²)}^{√(4−x²)}
      ∫_{z=−√(4−x²−y²)}^{√(4−x²−y²)} 1 dz dy dx.

Although rather piece‐wise, this is a perfectly good Cartesian setup.

---

2)  Cylindrical coordinates 

Recall x= r cosθ, y= r sinθ, z=z, and dV= r dr dθ dz.  The cylinder x²+y²=1 is r=1 and the sphere x²+y²+z²=4 is z=±√(4−r²).  Hence

Vol(R)
= ∫_{θ=0}^{2π}
    ∫_{r=1}^{2}
      ∫_{z=−√(4−r²)}^{√(4−r²)}
        r dz dr dθ.

---

3)  Spherical coordinates

Recall x=ρ sinφ cosθ, y=ρ sinφ sinθ, z=ρ cosφ, dV=ρ² sinφ dρ dφ dθ.  
The sphere is ρ=2.  The cylinder x²+y²=1 becomes ρ sinφ=1 ⇒ ρ=1/ sinφ.  
Thus for each φ we only include ρ from 1/ sinφ up to 2, and we must have 1/sinφ≤2 ⇒ sinφ≥½ ⇒ φ∈[π/6,5π/6].  Hence

Vol(R)
= ∫_{θ=0}^{2π}
    ∫_{φ=π/6}^{5π/6}
      ∫_{ρ=1/ sinφ}^{2}
        ρ² sinφ dρ dφ dθ.

---

Any one of these three integrals, when evaluated, gives the volume of the region inside x²+y²+z²=4 and outside x²+y²=1.
